<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-02-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-02-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="915" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d915">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/2746.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of War</gloss> to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">War Department</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-07">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 7, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Following telegram, dated El Paso, Texas, February 6, 1912, from Colonel
                            Edgar Z. Steever, Fourth Cavalry, commanding Fort Bliss, Texas, repeated
                            for your information: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>Thirteen mounted and armed Mexicans invaded United States
                                    territory at Noria, New Mexico, thirty miles west of El Paso
                                    today. Immediately sent detachment by train which captured the
                                    whole outfit and sixteen horses. Prisoners now in guard house.
                                    Railroad officials afraid the Mexicans intended to hold up
                                    express trains; Noria only two miles north of international
                                    boundary. Juárez continues tranquil.</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">H. L. Stimson.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
